<|startoftext|>Headline:Senator says U.N. does not want to intervene on Venezuela: sources
Content: "GENEVA (Reuters) - Venezuela s U.N. ambassador has urged other countries to step in and call its neighbor to restore diplomatic ties, a senior U.N. official said on Tuesday, after U.N. diplomats raised concern for the dire humanitarian condition of Venezuela s battered economy. A U.N. observer said in an open letter the United Nations condemned what she calls Venezuela s gross violation of international humanitarian law. Venezuela has taken several steps to try to restore its relationship with the United Nations, which said it has imposed new economic sanctions and cut its economic imports. It has cut cooperation with foreign aid agencies, shut its biggest trade and investment arm and imposed a ban on state-backed coal-fired power as well as a ban on imports of petroleum products. The United Nations has also said it is concerned that sanctions adopted in last year against certain North Korean companies in retaliation for its currency problems in defiance of United Nations sanctions and the sale of Venezuelan food products with the U.N. seal could be used to force other countries to lift their own sanctions. U.N. Secretary-General Antonio Guterres said the United Nations had no desire to impose measures on North Korea in reprisal for its latest aggression. He added, however, that the United Nations should work with its two neighboring countries for a humanitarian solution, instead of military intervention against North Korea.          But U.N. Secretary-General Antonio Guterres said it can work with other countries. He said the decision was not taken lightly and was taken in a matter of common defense ...           The diplomat s letter  , signed by the ambassadors of Colombia, Panama, and Honduras, also came as tensions in Venezuela escalated in recent weeks.      Venezuela is carrying out the most brutal crackdown of sanctions on the country, which it has called a war on people, including the killing of more than 700 people this week and more than 1,000 in the country s more than two dozen oil pipelines. The Trump administration has said that the United States has been intervening in Venezuela s elections as U.S. and Venezuelan officials have said Washington is assisting in Venezuela s efforts to end Maduro s socialist rule. The U.N. said the United Nations was concerned about Venezuela s human rights abuses, accusing its government of being  a         , and criticized Washington for using its U.N. authority to block an election that was not fair. It also called upon U.N. member states to  exercise their influence to ensure that this administration fully respects the rights of persons at the heart of Venezuela, including peaceful political processes, including a return to full and democratically organised elections,  the U.N.S. letter said.       U.N. Ambassador Nikki Haley said last week that the United States stood with the Venezuelan government and its people, and asked the world for diplomatic and economic support to end the civil war.        ",<|endoftext|>
